arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 53 consists of the threshold and doorway between the “bathroom” and the hallway to the east. As with many of the other features in the bathroom, the walls are part of the larger construction and are differentiated along functionality instead of definitive breaks in construction. The threshold is a single hewn sandstone ashlar oriented north-south between the two walls. Each of the walls consist of door jams, with the cut out corner on their east faces. Both of the walls are seven courses high and two rows wide, made of hewn sandstone ashlars. As this locus is an essential part of the “bathroom,” it is phased to the main construction period of the bath complex (Stage 3).
Doorway and threshold of the “bathroom” to the “hypocaust room”
1.40 m north south-by- 0.65 m east west.
